Tuấn Đăng Khoa Lê is an Intern Network Administrator/Engineer with academic project experience in network design, deployment, and management. Their core expertise encompasses fundamental networking concepts such as Subnetting, VLAN, VPN (including IPSec VPN), DHCP, DNS, and Basic Firewall Configuration, alongside practical application of Routing Protocols, Network Security principles, Troubleshooting, and Network Monitoring. Through academic projects, Tuấn developed a comprehensive Network Management System (NMS) on Windows Server and Ubuntu, focusing on real-time monitoring, unauthorized connection alerts, critical device error detection, and automated reporting to ensure internal network security. Additionally, they designed and deployed a robust network model for a medium-sized enterprise utilizing Cisco Router/Switch devices within Packet Tracer and GNS3 environments, implementing advanced routing protocols and security measures like VPN and firewall configurations to optimize performance, stability, and information safety.
Technically, Tuấn is proficient with essential networking tools and platforms including Cisco Router/Switch hardware, network simulation tools like Packet Tracer and GNS3, and operating systems such as Windows Server and Ubuntu. Their foundational knowledge extends to critical network services and security practices, including User Permission Management, LAN/WAN architecture, and the implementation of various network security techniques. This profile highlights a strong academic foundation in Computer Networks and Data Communications, demonstrating hands-on capability in network infrastructure setup, security hardening, and operational monitoring.